    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSince commit e8b3ed74bca4bd6ececcc240f816451bef7fd58c, there is stricter validation of the options set via `vim.o`. \r\n\r\nFor example, setting `vim.o.textwidth = \"120\"` gives you this error:\r\n\r\n> ```E5113: Error while calling lua chunk: /Users/danstrokirk/.config/nvim/lua/config/settings.lua:8: Invalid value for option 'textwidth': expected Number, got String \"120\"```\r\n\r\nThe related code is here:\r\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/e8b3ed74bca4bd6ececcc240f816451bef7fd58c/src/nvim/option.c#L3726\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim -u NORC --cmd 'lua vim.o.textwidth = \"12\"'\r\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI'm not opposed to this stricter validation, and rewriting my config file was pretty fast, but I was confused about this change at first and tried reading about it in `:help news`. Adding a note about breaking changes for this would be very useful.\r\n\r\nIt's likely many users are relying on the string coercion behaviour in their config files, so possibly it might make sense to keep some sort of type conversion from strings, but I'm not sure about that, it's not _too_ difficult to update. The only issue might be if seldomly maintained plugins are relying on the old functionality.\r\n\r\n(I'm also partly writing this issue for anyone that experiences the same error and is confused from where it came!)\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\ne8b3ed74bca4bd6ececcc240f816451bef7fd58c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\niterm2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nHomebrew + build from repo to bisect",
    "closed_at": "2023-08-25T22:38:43Z",
